<br>
 Nov. 7<br>
<br>
Unless scientists find ways to cut astronauts' radiation exposure in space, staff turnover aboard the International Space Station will remain high and long-duration travel beyond Earth orbit a violation of NASA's own flight safety rules, agency officials said Thursday.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is not an easily solved scientific problem,&quot; said Paul Todd, chairman of an American Society for Gravitational and Space Biology Space Radiation Health symposium.<br>
<br>
Young women are particularly vulnerable to cell and tissue damage from space radiation. The greatest threat is an increased chance of developing breast, ovarian or uterine cancer, said Francis Cucinotta, director of Space Radiation Health at NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston. Men's bodies overall are less sensitive to radiation, but even so, a typical 45-year-old male astronaut will only be able to spend about 250 days in space before bumping into NASA's limit: 3 percent above normal cancer risk.<br>
<br>
On Earth, the atmosphere shields the planet from dangerous celestial radiation, which come from three primary sources: the sun, trapped particles in Earth's magnetic field and high-energy cosmic rays, which pose the most severe health threats to astronauts.<br>
<br>
NASA has set a goal to improve radiation exposure predictions, understand how radiation affects the human body and design countermeasures so that low-Earth orbiting crewmembers can boost cumulative space missions to an average of 380 days in space, said Walter Schimmerling, head NASA's radiation programs at the agency's Washington, D.C. headquarters.<br>
<br>
A request for $10.1 million under the agency's new Space Radiation Initiative is pending before Congress. In addition, NASA is spending $44 million to build a facility at Brookhaven National Laboratory to simulate the effects of various types of space radiation. Current radiation predictions stem from studies of atomic bomb survivors and are not readily applicable to the longer-term, lower energy radiation doses astronauts experience in space.<br>
<br>
NASA is sponsoring research to look into a variety of shielding technologies and materials. Lead, for example, turns out to be not a good choice since high-energy radiation can fragment the lead, causing its particles to become radioactive. The best shielding, researchers have found, is liquid hydrogen.<br>
<br>
&quot;Everything that goes on a spacecraft is potentially considered radiation shielding,&quot; said Cucinotta.<br>
<br>
The agency also is exploring biological countermeasures for radiation exposure, such as antioxidants and other pharmaceutical treatments.<br>
<br>
&quot;We really don't understand the biological effects of radiation,&quot; said Cucinotta. &quot;But we have the tools to solve the problem.&quot;<br>
